For a quantitative description of Raman scattering, the KHD formula is the
 standard, frequency domain expression for the scattering cross section
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tannor_introduction_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{fi}^{\mathrm{3D}}\left(\omega_{S},\omega_{I}\right)=\frac{8\pi\omega_{I}\omega_{S}^{3}}{9c^{4}}\sum_{\rho,\lambda}\left|\left[\alpha_{fi}\left(\omega_{I}\right)\right]^{\nu\nu^{\prime}}\right|^{2},\label{eq:KHD-cross-section-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the polarizability is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}\left[\alpha_{fi}\left(\omega_{I}\right)\right]^{\nu\nu^{\prime}}=-\sum_{k,n} & \left(\frac{\left\langle \psi_{f}\right|\widehat{\mu}^{\nu}\left|\psi_{k,n}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{k,n}\right|\widehat{\mu}^{\nu^{\prime}}\left|\psi_{i}\right\rangle }{\varepsilon_{i}+\hbar\omega_{I}-\varepsilon_{kn}+i\hbar\gamma}\right.\\
 & \left.+\frac{\left\langle \psi_{f}\right|\widehat{\mu}^{\nu^{\prime}}\left|\psi_{k,n}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{n}\right|\widehat{\mu}^{\nu}\left|\psi_{i}\right\rangle }{\varepsilon_{f}-\hbar\omega_{I}-\varepsilon_{kn}+i\hbar\gamma}\right),
\end{split}
\label{eq:KHD-polarizability-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The frequency of the incident photons is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{I}$
\end_inset

 and the frequency of the scattered photons is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{S}$
\end_inset

; these frequencies satisfy energy conservation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{S}=\varepsilon_{i}+\hbar\omega_{I}-\varepsilon_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
polarizability
\end_layout

\end_inset

The KHD formula is known as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sum-over-states
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 formula since the polarizability expression requires a summation over all
 possible intermediate states 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{k,n}$
\end_inset

 where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 labels electronic states and the index 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 labels vibrational states corresponding to electronic states.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mu}^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 denotes the transition dipole moment operator for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\left\{ x,y,z\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The linewidth 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the average lifetime of the intermediate state.
