\begin_layout Subsection
Three-level System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
3LS Hamiltonian 
\end_layout

\end_inset

To quantify the KHD Raman scattering formalism, we consider a model system
 with three vibronic states: two lower energy states for an electronic ground
 state with different vibrational modes: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|gn_{1}\right\rangle \equiv\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|gn_{1}^{\prime}\right\rangle \equiv\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and one for an excited state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|en_{2}\right\rangle \equiv\left|2\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 We assume the energies of the vibronic states are 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}\le\varepsilon_{1}<\varepsilon_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the electric dipole interactions couple the ground and excited states
 only.
 Thus, the electronic Hamiltonian is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\varepsilon_{0} & 0 & {\cal V}_{02}\\
0 & \varepsilon_{1} & {\cal V}_{12}\\
{\cal V}_{02}^{^{*}} & {\cal V}_{12}^{*} & \varepsilon_{2}
\end{array}\right)\label{eq:Hamiltonian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the electric dipole coupling is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\cal V}_{ij}=-\int\mathrm{d}x\mathbf{E}\left(x,t\right)\cdot\boldsymbol{{\cal P}}_{ij}\left(x\right).\label{eq:electric-dipole-coupling}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in a 1D space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Incoming field
\end_layout

\end_inset

For frequency domain measurement, consider a single-mode incoming continuous
 wave (CW) electromagnetic field with frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{I}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathbf{E}_{I}\left(x,t\right) & = & \frac{A_{I}}{\sqrt{\epsilon_{0}}}\cos\left(k_{I}x-\omega_{I}t\right)\hat{\mathbf{z}}\label{eq:E_CW}\\
\mathbf{B}_{I}\left(x,t\right) & = & -\sqrt{\mu_{0}}A_{I}\sin\left(k_{I}x-\omega_{I}t\right)\hat{\mathbf{y}}\label{eq:B_CW}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{I}=ck_{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{I}$
\end_inset

 is the amplitude of the incoming field.
 We assume the spatial size of the polarization is small in space, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{{\cal P}}_{ij}\left(x\right)\approx\mu_{ij}\delta\left(x\right)\hat{\mathbf{z}}$
\end_inset

, so that the electric dipole interactions are approximated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\mathrm{d}x\mathbf{E}\left(x,t\right)\cdot\boldsymbol{{\cal P}}_{ij}\left(x\right)\approx\mu_{ij}\frac{A_{I}}{\sqrt{\epsilon_{0}}}\cos\left(\omega_{I}t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
KHD
\end_layout

\end_inset

For light scattering in a 1D space, the scattering cross section is defined
 as the ratio between the number of photons scattered per time divided by
 the number of photons incident per time.
 With this definition, the KHD Raman cross section becomes in 1D (see Appendix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Scattering-Cross-section"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{fi}^{\mathrm{1D}}\left(\omega_{S},\omega_{I}\right)=\frac{\omega_{I}\omega_{S}}{2c^{2}}\left|\alpha_{fi}^{\mathrm{1D}}\left(\omega_{I}\right)\right|^{2}\label{eq:KHD-cross-section-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a three-level system, the KHD expression for the polarizability is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}\alpha_{fi}^{\mathrm{1D}}\left(\omega_{I}\right)=- & \left(\frac{\mu_{02}\mu_{12}}{\varepsilon_{i}+\hbar\omega_{I}-\varepsilon_{2}+i\hbar\gamma}\right.\\
 & \left.+\frac{\mu_{02}\mu_{12}}{\varepsilon_{f}-\hbar\omega_{I}-\varepsilon_{2}+i\hbar\gamma}\right).
\end{split}
\label{eq:KHD-polarizability-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
linewidth
\end_layout

\end_inset

Here we take linewidth 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 to be the average lifetime for the electronic transitions of the excited
 state:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\gamma}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{\kappa_{02}}+\frac{1}{\kappa_{12}}\right),\label{eq:averge_width}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the corresponding Fermi's golden rule (FGR) rates are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{fi}=\frac{\varepsilon_{i}-\varepsilon_{f}}{\hbar^{2}\epsilon_{0}c}\mu_{fi}^{2}.\label{eq:FGR_rate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
resonance
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the case of resonant Stokes or anti-Stokes Raman scattering (where the
 incident photon lines up with the excited state, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}+\hbar\omega_{I}=\varepsilon_{2}$
\end_inset

), the first term in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:KHD-polarizability-2"

\end_inset

 dominates.
 Resonant Raman scattering signals are composed of two signals: (i) When
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{I}=\varepsilon_{2}-\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the scattered photon energy is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{S}=\varepsilon_{2}-\varepsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

, the polarizability term with 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{10}^{\mathrm{1D}}\left(\omega_{I}\right)$
\end_inset

) leads to a Stokes Raman peak (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{S}<\omega_{I}$
\end_inset

).
 (ii) When 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{I}=\varepsilon_{2}-\varepsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

 the scattered photon energy is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega_{S}=\varepsilon_{2}-\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

, the polarizability term with 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{01}^{\mathrm{1D}}\left(\omega_{I}\right)$
\end_inset

) leads to an anti-Stokes Raman peak (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{S}>\omega_{I}$
\end_inset

).
 Obviously, anti-Stokes Raman scattering can occur only state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is occupied at steady state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
off-resonance
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the case that the incident photon does not line up with any excited state,
 the excitation is detuned far off resonance (known as off-resonance Raman
 scattering).
 In this case, the intermediate state of the light scattering process is
 a visual state, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{k}=\varepsilon_{i}+\hbar\omega_{I}$
\end_inset

, and the two terms in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:KHD-polarizability-2"

\end_inset

 both contribute meaningfully to the Raman cross section.
 Of course, for a weak field, scattered photons are always dominated by
 Rayleigh scattering (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{S}=\omega_{I}$
\end_inset

).
 
