We write the total EM field in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}=\mathbf{E}_{I}+\mathbf{E}_{S}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}=\mathbf{B}_{I}+\mathbf{B}_{S}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}_{S}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{S}$
\end_inset

 are the scattered EM fields.
 For a CW field given by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:E_CW"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:B_CW"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}_{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{I}$
\end_inset

 satisfy source-less Maxwell's equations, so we can treat the CW field as
 a standalone external field.
 Therefore, for underlying Ehrenfest dynamics, the scattered fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}_{S}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{S}$
\end_inset

 satisfy Maxwell's equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{B}_{S} & = & -\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\mathbf{E}_{S},\label{eq:maxwell_BE}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{E}_{S} & = & c^{2}\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\mathbf{B}_{S}-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\mathbf{J},\label{eq:maxwell_EB}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the average current is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{J}\left(x,t\right)=\sum_{i=2}\sum_{f=0,1}2\left(\varepsilon_{f}-\varepsilon_{i}\right)\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{fi}\left(t\right)\right]\boldsymbol{{\cal P}}_{fi}\left(x\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


