\begin_layout Plain Layout
By definition, the photon cross section is the number of photons emitted
 per time, divided by the incident photon flux.
 In 1D, the incident photon flux is obtained by Einstein relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{N_{I}c}{L}=\frac{A_{I}^{2}c}{2\hbar\omega_{I}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Following second order perturbation theory
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tannor_introduction_2006"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the cross section for a 1D system can be obtained:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{fi}^{\mathrm{1D}}\left(\omega_{S},\omega_{I}\right)=\frac{\omega_{S}\omega_{I}}{2c^{2}}\left|\alpha_{fi}\left(\omega_{I}\right)\right|^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Following Tannor's approach in Ref.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


